ChatGPT said:
No worries â€” this is one of the most common issues when using Ansible with AWS EC2. Letâ€™s go step-by-step to ensure your authentication setup is correct and how to fix it if it fails.

âœ… What This Inventory Means
ini
Copy
Edit
[ec2_targets]
<EC2_1_PUBLIC_IP> ansible_user=ubuntu ansible_ssh_private_key_file=~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem
<EC2_2_PUBLIC_IP> ansible_user=ubuntu ansible_ssh_private_key_file=~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem
ansible_user=ubuntu â†’ EC2 default username (used for Ubuntu AMIs).

ansible_ssh_private_key_file=~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem â†’ Path to your private key.

ğŸš¨ Common Mistakes and Fixes
âŒ 1. Wrong ansible_user
âœ… For Ubuntu AMIs â†’ ubuntu

âœ… For Amazon Linux 2 â†’ ec2-user

Fix:

ini
Copy
Edit
<EC2_IP> ansible_user=ec2-user  # If you're using Amazon Linux
âŒ 2. Wrong Key Path or Permissions
The file must exist and be readable only by you (chmod 400).

Check it like this:

bash
Copy
Edit
ls -l ~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem
Should show:

bash
Copy
Edit
-r-------- 1 you you 1675 date time ec2-key.pem
Fix:

bash
Copy
Edit
chmod 400 ~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem
âŒ 3. Wrong or Missing Public IP
Make sure the IPs are:

Public, not private IPs

The EC2 instance is running

You can SSH manually:

bash
Copy
Edit
ssh -i ~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem ubuntu@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>
If that doesn't work, Ansible won't either.

âŒ 4. Port 22 Not Open in Security Group
In AWS console â†’ EC2 â†’ Security Groups

Inbound rule must allow:

vbnet
Copy
Edit
Type: SSH
Port: 22
Source: Your public IP or 0.0.0.0/0 (temporarily)
âŒ 5. Key is in wrong format (Putty .ppk)
If you're using Windows and have a .ppk file (from PuTTY), you need to convert it to .pem using PuTTYgen.

ğŸ§ª Test SSH Access Manually First
Before you run Ansible, test SSH to each EC2:

bash
Copy
Edit
ssh -i ~/.ssh/ec2-key.pem ubuntu@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>
If this works â†’ authentication is fine.

If this fails â†’ fix the SSH/auth issue before running Ansible.

